1. Data Preprocessing

1.1. Loading Dataset

In this lab, we will perform KNN classification on the FIFA Player 20 dataset from Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/stefanoleone992/fifa-20-complete-player-dataset). The provided datasets include the players data for the Career Mode from FIFA 15 to FIFA 20 ("players_20.csv"). The data, consisting of more than 100 variables, allow multiple comparison of the same players across the last 6 version of the videogame. We aim at predicting the wage_eur of a player using international_reputation, skill_moves, shooting, passing, dribbling and defending. To make it a classification problem, we create an indicator wage_binaryto represent whether a player’s wage exceeding the population median.

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
# library(corrplot)
library(ggplot2)

dat = read.csv("players_20.csv")
dat = dat %>% select("wage_eur", "international_reputation", "skill_moves", "shooting", "passing", "dribbling", "defending")
dat$wage_binary = factor(dat$wage_eur > median(dat$wage_eur))
levels(dat$wage_binary) = c("Low", "High")

2.1. Scatterplot Matrix

The ggpairs() function of the GGally package allows to build a great scatterplot matrix.

Scatterplots of each pair of numeric variable are drawn on the upper right part of the figure. Pearson correlation is displayed on the lower left. Variable distribution (given by kernel density estimation) is available on the diagonal.

library(GGally)
ggpairs(dat.train, axisLabels = 'none',
        upper = list(continuous = 'points', combo = 'dot'),
        lower = list(continuous = 'cor', combo = 'dot'),
        diag = list(continuous = 'densityDiag')) +
  theme_bw()

Converting between wide table and long table is a useful way to match various inputs of functions. We convert our table from wide to long to draw boxplots with subfigures using ggplot2.

# Transform from wide table to long table

3. KNN classification

library(class)

We need to pull out the outcome variable and the design matrix for the training and test data.

train_label = dat.train %>% .$wage_binary 
train_x = dat.train %>% select("international_reputation", "skill_moves", "shooting", "passing", "dribbling", "defending")

test_label = dat.test %>% .$wage_binary 
test_x = dat.test %>% select("international_reputation", "skill_moves", "shooting", "passing", "dribbling", "defending")

3.1. Data Standardization

As we can see in the data exploration, the variables have different ranges. It is very important to scale both training and test data in the same way. In other words, we need to use same mean and standard deviation to transform both training and test data. Those desired mean and standard deviation used for scaling should only come from the training data.

mean_train = colMeans(train_x)
std_train = sqrt(diag(var(train_x)))
# training data
train_x = scale(train_x, center = mean_train, scale = std_train)
# test data
test_x = scale(test_x, center = mean_train, scale = std_train)
  • The center = ... argument specifies the mean for scaling.
  • The scale = ... arguments specifies the standard deviation used for scaling.
  • With the additional arguments, the scale() function will perform \[ x_{i}^{\operatorname{std}}=\frac{x_{i}-\text{mean}_{\text{train}}}{\text{std}_{\text{train}}}. \]

3.2. KNN with K = 1

Now the knn() function can be used to predict whether wage_eur is high or low.

The function requires four inputs:

  • train: matrix or data frame of training set cases;
  • test: matrix or data frame of test set cases;
  • cl: factor of true classifications of training set, i.e. labels;
  • k: number of neighbours considered.
set.seed(1)
pred_train = knn(train_x, 
               train_x, 
               train_label, 
               k = 1)

pred_test = knn(train_x, 
               test_x, 
               train_label, 
               k = 1)

3.3. Confusion Matrix

The table() function can be used to produce a confusion matrix in order to determine how many observations were correctly or incorrectly classified.

# Pull out the true responses for the test data
table(pred_train, train_label)
##           train_label
## pred_train  Low High
##       Low  6041   11
##       High   13 5305
mean(pred_train == train_label)
## [1] 0.9978892
table(pred_test, test_label)
##          test_label
## pred_test  Low High
##      Low  1991  666
##      High  595 1620
mean(pred_test == test_label)
## [1] 0.7411741

We notice that KNN using K = 1 does not give us 0 errors on training set. How to explain this?

The test results using K = 1 are not very good compared to training errors, which means we have strong overfit.

3.4. KNN with Varing K

We further seek a best K.

k_range = c(5, 10, 20, 25, 50, 200, 400)
train_error = c()
test_error = c()
for(i in 1:length(k_range)){
  pred_train <- knn(train_x, 
               train_x, 
               train_label, 
               k = k_range[i])
  train_error[i] = mean(pred_train != train_label)
  pred_test = knn(train_x, 
               test_x, 
               train_label, 
               k = k_range[i])
  test_error[i] = mean(pred_test != test_label)
}

For each iteration in the for loop, we fit a KNN model using the same dataset, but with different choice of K as k_range[i]. We compute the training and test error rate each round.

3.5. Plotting Training and Test Errors

Let’s create a plot for all those training and test error rates. Recall we want to plot error vs 1/K as smaller K corresponds to more complex models.

errors = data.frame(train_error, test_error, k_range)
ggplot(errors, aes(x = 1/k_range)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = train_error), col = "red") + geom_point(aes(y = train_error), col = "red") +
  geom_line(aes(y = test_error), col = "blue") + geom_point(aes(y = test_error), col = "blue") +
  ylab("Error Rate") + xlab("1/K") + ggtitle("Training and test error rate for KNN") + theme_minimal()

Which K would you prefer, given the plot? Why?

4.2. Imputation Methods

Imputation is the process of replacing missing data with substituted values.

Two simple imputation methods are mean imputation and median imputation.

(1) Mean imputation

# Copy training and test data
dat.train.mean = dat.train
dat.test.mean = dat.test

# Mean imputation, only column 4 - 7 have NA's
for (i in 4:7){
  dat.train.mean[is.na(dat.train.mean[,i]),i] = mean(dat.train.mean[!is.na(dat.train.mean[,i]),i])
  dat.test.mean[is.na(dat.test.mean[,i]),i] = mean(dat.test.mean[!is.na(dat.test.mean[,i]),i])
}
summary(dat.train.mean)

(3) Predictive mean matching

We consider imputation by predictive mean matching (PMM), proposed by Donald B. Rubin and Roderick J.A. Little. The implementation details of PMM can be found at https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/mice/mice.pdf, page 115.

The function mice(), multivariate imputation by chained equations, creates multiple imputations for multivariate missing data.

dat.train.temp = mice(dat.train, m=1, maxit=50, meth='pmm', seed=2021)
dat.test.temp = mice(dat.test, m=1, maxit=50, meth='pmm', seed=2021)

The function requires five inputs:

  • data: the data frame for imputation;
  • m: the number of imputed datasets;
  • maxit: the number of iterations.
  • meth: the imputation method;
  • seed: an integer for setting the random number generator.

Now we can get back the completed dataset by using the complete() function.

dat.train.pmm = complete(dat.train.temp, 1)
dat.test.pmm = complete(dat.test.temp, 1)
summary(dat.train.pmm)

4.3. Fitting KNN on Imputed Data

We fit KNN again on imputed data.

# (1) Pulling out labels and design matrix
train_label = dat.train.pmm %>% .$wage_binary 
train_x = dat.train.pmm %>% select("international_reputation", "skill_moves", "shooting", "passing", "dribbling", "defending")

test_label = dat.test.pmm %>% .$wage_binary 
test_x = dat.test.pmm %>% select("international_reputation", "skill_moves", "shooting", "passing", "dribbling", "defending")

# (2) Standardization
mean_train = colMeans(train_x)
std_train = sqrt(diag(var(train_x)))
# training data
train_x = scale(train_x, center = mean_train, scale = std_train)
# test data
test_x = scale(test_x, center = mean_train, scale = std_train)

# (3) KNN with varing K
k_range = c(5, 10, 20, 25, 50, 200, 400)
train_error = c()
test_error = c()
for(i in 1:length(k_range)){
  pred_train <- knn(train_x, 
               train_x, 
               train_label, 
               k = k_range[i])
  train_error[i] = mean(pred_train != train_label)
  pred_test = knn(train_x, 
               test_x, 
               train_label, 
               k = k_range[i])
  test_error[i] = mean(pred_test != test_label)
}

# (4) Plotting error rate curves
errors = data.frame(train_error, test_error, k_range)
ggplot(errors, aes(x = 1/k_range)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = train_error), col = "red") + geom_point(aes(y = train_error), col = "red") +
  geom_line(aes(y = test_error), col = "blue") + geom_point(aes(y = test_error), col = "blue") +
  ylab("Error Rate") + xlab("1/K") + ggtitle("Training and test error rate for KNN") + theme_minimal()

The test error from dropping rows with missing data (section 3) can be viewed as a benchmark when comparing to imputation method.

Can we impute missing outcomes in the training set? Nope. If the outcome variable for an observation is missing, we will have to remove that observation.
